Aggregation of scores

Some measures are given by a single number (e.g., “weight”);
Others are computed by aggregating (e.g., summing) multiple numbers into one score (e.g., “cost of living”)

Interval scales (arbitrary zero)
°Celsius 0 = freezing point of water;
1 unit = 1/100 of the range between freezing (0°C) and boiling (100°C)
 °Fahrenheit 0 = freezing point of a brine solution (ice + water + salt);
1 unit = 1/180 of the range between freezing (32°F) and boiling (212°F)

Ratio scale (absolute zero)
°Kelvin 0 = absolute zero (complete absence of thermal energy);
1 unit = same magnitude as 1°C

Caution:
The 4 levels of measurement (N-O-I-R) were proposed by Stanley Smith Stevens in 1946;
